```bash
mkdir discord-bot
cd discord-bot
npm init -y
npm install discord.js
```

Create a `index.js` file in the project folder and add the following code:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const client = new Discord.Client();

// Replace with your bot token from the Discord Developer Portal
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN_HERE';

client.on('ready', () => {
    console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

// Slash command for banning a user
client.slashCommands.interactions('ban', {
    name: 'ban',
    description: 'Ban a user from the server.',
    options: [
        {
            name: 'user',
            description: 'The user to ban.',
            type: 'USER',
            required: true,
        },
    ],
    async execute(interaction) {
        const user = interaction.user;
        if (!user) return interaction.reply('Invalid user!');

        try {
            await interaction.member.ban(user);
            interaction.reply(`Banned ${user.username} successfully.`);
        } catch (error) {
            interaction.reply('Failed to ban the user. Please try again.');
        }
    },
});

client.login(token);
```

Replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN_HERE'` with your actual bot token, which you can obtain from the Discord Developer Portal.

This code sets up a simple Discord bot with a single slash command, "ban." The command takes a single argument, "user," which represents the user to be banned. When executed, it will ban the user from the server and send a confirmation message to the Discord chat.

