    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.4]
        \node[fill=white, draw=black, minimum size=1cm] (square) at (#1, #2) {};
        \node at (#1-0.2, #2-0.2) {$1$};
        \node at (#1+0.2, #2-0.2) {$2$};
        \node at (#1-0.2, #2+0.2) {$3$};
        \node at (#1+0.2, #2+0.2) {$4$};
        \node at (#1-0.5, #2) {$5$};
        \node at (#1+0.5, #2) {$6$};
        \node at (#1, #2-0.5) {$7$};
        \node at (#1, #2+0.5) {$8$};
    \end{tikzpicture}
}
```
3. Now, parse the FEN notation to create a list of square coordinates and their contents (white or black). For example, a typical FEN notation might look like this: `r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1`. Replace `r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1` with the actual FEN you want to represent.

4. Create a loop to draw each square based on the FEN coordinates and content. You can use the `foreach` loop from the `pgf` package:
```latex
\usepackage{pgf}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
    \foreach \x in {0, 1, ..., 7} {
        \foreach \y in {0, 1, ..., 7} {
            \ifcase\y
                \or \chessSquare{\x*8-0.5}{\y*8-0.5}{} % White square
                \or \chessSquare{\x*8+0.5}{\y*8-0.5}{} % Black square
